3) One‑liners for Embeddings (Concise Knowledge Snippets)
These short, declarative statements help retrieval models answer “what/why/how” quickly.
•	A resistor limits current in a circuit.

•	A capacitor stores electrical energy and releases it back when required.

•	An inductor passes DC and impedes AC due to inductive reactance.

•	A rheostat is a variable resistor used to adjust current.

•	A voltmeter measures potential difference between two points and is connected in parallel.

•	An ammeter measures current and is connected in series; it should have very low internal resistance.

•	A relay is an electrically operated switch controlling another circuit.

•	A circuit breaker trips to stop current when faults occur.

•	A slip ring induction motor offers high starting torque and good speed control.

•	A squirrel cage induction motor uses stator–rotor magnetic interaction to produce torque.

•	A DC motor converts DC electrical power into mechanical rotation.

•	An auto‑transformer provides variable/near‑unity ratio transformation and motor starting.
